{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640478"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:17:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:17:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17830"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17830"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.17,0,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76564"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10544"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17830"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5719"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25033"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76564"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman with end-stage chronic obstructive pulmonary disease is admitted to hospital with respiratory failure. After discussion with the patient and family, a decision is made to focus on comfort care rather than escalating medical interventions. The medical team documents \u0027not for intubation\u0027 in the medical record.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ethical approach being taken in this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Withdrawal or withholding of life-sustaining treatment","Provision of pain relief that may shorten life","Assisted suicide with physician supervision","Continuation of all possible medical interventions","Administration of medications to end life"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWithdrawal or withholding of life-sustaining treatment\u003C/strong\u003E correctly defines passive euthanasia, which is the approach being taken in this case by documenting \u0027not for intubation\u0027 and focusing on comfort care rather than escalating interventions. This involves allowing a natural death to occur by not initiating or by discontinuing life-prolonging interventions such as mechanical ventilation, artificial nutrition, or dialysis when they are deemed futile or not in accordance with the patient\u0027s wishes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvision of pain relief that may shorten life\u003C/strong\u003E describes the principle of double effect, where providing appropriate symptom control is the primary intention, even if there may be a foreseeable but unintended effect on survival.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAssisted suicide with physician supervision\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the practice where a doctor provides means for a patient to end their own life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuation of all possible medical interventions\u003C/strong\u003E represents full medical care, which is the opposite approach to passive euthanasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministration of medications to end life\u003C/strong\u003E describes active euthanasia, which involves deliberately hastening death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPassive euthanasia is generally considered ethically and legally acceptable when performed within established guidelines and with appropriate consent. It recognises that there are circumstances where continuing or initiating life-sustaining treatment may not be in the patient\u0027s best interests.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Passive euthanasia involves withdrawing or withholding life-sustaining treatment, allowing natural death to occur.","Passive euthanasia is legally permitted in many jurisdictions when performed according to established medical guidelines and ethical principles.","The principle of double effect distinguishes between intended outcomes and foreseen but unintended consequences in end-of-life care."],"references":["Euthanasia, human rights and the law | Australian Human Rights Commission [Internet]. humanrights.gov.au. Available from: https://humanrights.gov.au/our-work/age-discrimination/publications/euthanasia-human-rights-and-law#Heading95"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17830"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62061"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T18:27:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T08:02:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10544"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76564"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"descript